The communists are suspicious of the overtures made by social fascists. However, they will keep an eye on us until they figure out what we're up to.

@kpd_rectification_of_history

One stumbling block for our relations with the KPD is our history of conflict, dating back to 1918 and 1919. The KPD is especially contemptuous of Gustav Noske, the SPD bloodhound who ordered the violent suppression of the Spartacist uprising and other KPD revolutionary actions. They also blame us for the deaths of Rosa Luxemburg and Karl Liebknecht, two KPD leaders who were killed on our orders during the suppression of the uprising.

For further improvements in KPD relations, it might be necessary to expel Noske, hold some sort of commemoration for Luxemburg and Liebknecht, and do other minimal symbolic gestures.

- @yes_history: Yes, we must apologize for our past actions.
- @no_history: No, we have no need to apologize.

@yes_history
on-arrival: reformist_dissent += 12; reformist_strength -= 2; neorevisionist_dissent += 5; left_dissent -= 6; left_strength += 5; kpd_rectified_history = 1; z_relation -= 6; dvp_relation -= 6; ddp_relation -= 4; kpd_relation += 8*(1-dissent); coalition_dissent += 1

As part of normalizing relations with the KPD, we have to acknowledge the wrongdoings of our past. We have expelled Noske, and have held public commemorations for those killed by troops during the uprisings. 

Even these empty gestures lead to tensions with the passivists and reformists within our party, and criticism from the conservative and liberal parties who refuse to see the workers as human beings.

@no_history
on-arrival: kpd_relation -= 3

We have no need to apologize for the actions of Ebert and Noske; we are bloodthirsty ghouls who lust for the deaths of the proletariat.


